My New Love for noVNC

10-26-2023

I am always on the lookout for opportunities to make my work easier. Whether it is a resource that helps take care of administrative tasks for an engagement or a new tool for getting the extra little bit of recon that leads to successful compromise, there is usually a solution for every problem. To be honest, the whole process of looking for resources to add to my toolkit a bit cathartic, especially when finding something that works. That is where noVNC comes in. Since there is lots of documentation on how to install and configure noVNC, I am not going to do that here, but I am going to tell you why I have found it so useful.

What is noVNC?

According to the noVNC website, "noVNC is both a VNC client JavaScript library as well as an application built on top of that library. noVNC runs well in any modern browser including mobile browsers (iOS and Android)". Simply put, it allows for a remote desktop interface in your browser.

noVNC for Kali Linux

I first found noVNC while conducting an engagement (we will cover the use case associated with that scenario later) and immediately knew that there was a lot that could be done with this. The first things that came to my mind was my Raspberry Pi 4. I have lots of uses for my Pi, especially as a nice little drop box, but in this instance I found that running it as a Kali Linux server at home was of interest. Typically you need to connect the Pi to a monitor, but with noVNC I am able to use my browser to access my Kali desktop remotely, giving me the flexibility to use not just my laptop but my iPad as well. It has turned out to be a nice little lab setup and pointed me in the direction of my next idea.

In the past, I have always maintained a local Kali VM on my machine, which worked just fine but limited my flexibility. On top of that, storing engagement data locally is usually not the greatest idea as making sure that proper cleanup takes place can be difficult. Ultimately being able to stand up a disposable Kali instance remotely and having all of the benefits of a full interface becomes a very attractive option. By adding a few lines of code to install noVNC in my setup script, I am able to launch fully functioning Kali boxes with ease!

Phishing with noVNC

Like I said before, my initial introduction to noVNC came during and engagement. I found my self in a situation needing to by pass MFA for a popular authentication service and sadly evilginx2 was no longer effective against this service (I still love evilginx2 by the way). Thankfully, while doing a little research, I stumbled upon an awesome article by mr.d0x. Configuration was easy, and the results were amazing. I can't go into detail around what exactly was done, but lets just say that this Browser in the Browser attack can do some serious damage. With that said, there are a few things to consider. First, scalability can be a little tricky so being strategic with your use of noVNC for spear phishing scenarios is key. Second, it is essentially a remote desktop connection so make sure that you are limiting access to resources on the machine just in case.

In Conclusion

I have really been enjoying using noVNC and keep finding more and more use cases for it. I hope that this has sparked your interest as well and you have as much fun as I have! Listed below are some resources worth checking out:

  • https://novnc.com/info.html
  • https://github.com/novnc/noVNC
  • https://mrd0x.com/bypass-2fa-using-novnc/
